    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-10-06T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-10-06T10:00:00-05:00" n="165"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d165">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.5/10–651: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Deputy Representative on the North Atlantic
                        Council</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SCM1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Spofford</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d165fn1">Repeated to Paris personal for <persName
                            corresp="#p_PPR1">Porter</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MDI1"
                            >MacArthur</persName> and to Heidelberg personal for <persName
                            corresp="#p_HGTT1">Handy</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-10-06T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 6, 1951–4 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Depto1">Depto</gloss> 426. Personal for <persName
                        corresp="#p_CTD1">Cabot</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_NFC1"
                        >Nash</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_HNE1">Halaby</persName> and
                        <persName corresp="#p_GL1">Gordon</persName> (limit distribution). Please
                    refer <gloss target="#t_Todep1">Todep</gloss> 213.<note n="2" xml:id="d165fn2"
                        >Dated October 14, <ref target="#pg_294">p. 294</ref>.</note> Since the
                        <gloss target="#t_ECC1">ECC</gloss> cable of July 20 (<gloss
                        target="#t_Depto1">Depto</gloss> 88)<note n="3" xml:id="d165fn3">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_223">p. 223</ref>.</note>
                    recommending offshore procurement program, which was discussed and agreed upon
                    in the joint <gloss target="#t_ISAC1">ISAC</gloss>-<gloss target="#t_ECC1"
                        >ECC</gloss> meeting of July 30 (<gloss target="#t_Todep1">Todep</gloss>
                        67)<note n="4" xml:id="d165fn4">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_231">p. 231</ref>.</note> we
                    have been concerned as to our progress toward getting ahead with this approach
                    to the problem of increasing Eur production, which has been kicked back and
                    forth between here and Washington since February. In the meantime, and
                    particularly in the last few weeks, we have been receiving requests for
                    information, suggestions and prodding from all quarters. As a result, and in
                    line with our earlier action and obvious interest in the matter, we have had
                    some preliminary staff work done and put the item on the agenda for the next
                        <gloss target="#t_ECC1">ECC</gloss> meeting to try to pull loose ends
                    together here and to get off some coordinated recommendations. If these were to
                    be of any use it seemed to me that they should be made earlier rather than later
                    and preferably before final decisions are taken.</p>
                <p>I am still of this opinion. I am not impressed by the argument that <gloss
                        target="#t_ECC1">ECC</gloss> consideration of the matter will “produce
                    nothing but delay and confusion”. In the first place I doubt whether anything
                        <gloss target="#t_ECC1">ECC</gloss> can do would add to our rapidly growing
                    stockpile of both these items; in the second place, you can always find your way
                    out of the dilemma by disregarding the recommendations, for which precedent can
                    be found.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SCM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Spofford</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
